## Constexpr Functions (Part 2)

A `constexpr` function can do more than return a simple arithmetic expression. In C++20, the rules are broad enough that most ordinary function bodies compile at constant time, including local variables, loops, conditionals, and even calls to other `constexpr` functions.

### What's allowed inside a constexpr function

- Local variable declarations (including `constexpr` locals)
- `if` / `else`, `switch`, and all loop forms
- Calls to other `constexpr` or `consteval` functions
- Most standard library algorithms and containers when their implementations are `constexpr`-qualified

What remains off-limits: `goto`, non-literal-type variables, `static` local variables, and anything with undefined behavior.

### Compile-time vs runtime execution

A `constexpr` function is not *forced* to run at compile time. It runs at compile time only when called in a constant-expression context — for example, as the initializer of a `constexpr` variable or as a template argument. Called with a runtime value, it behaves like a normal function. Use `consteval` (covered in *Constexpr functions*) when you want to *require* compile-time evaluation.

```cpp
#include <print>

constexpr int digit_sum(int n) {
    int total = 0;
    while (n > 0) {
        total += n % 10;
        n /= 10;
    }
    return total;
}

int main() {
    constexpr int compile_time = digit_sum(12345); // evaluated at compile time
    int runtime_input = 12345;
    int runtime_result = digit_sum(runtime_input);  // evaluated at runtime
    std::println("{} {}", compile_time, runtime_result); // 15 15
}
```

### Checking compile-time context

Sometimes you want a function that behaves differently depending on *when* it runs. `std::is_constant_evaluated()` returns `true` when the call is in a constant-expression context. This lets you swap in a compile-time-safe algorithm without losing runtime performance — a common pattern in standard library implementations.

```cpp
constexpr double fast_sqrt(double x) {
    if (std::is_constant_evaluated())
        return /* compile-time algorithm */ x; // simplified placeholder
    return __builtin_sqrt(x);                  // fast intrinsic at runtime
}
```

### Practical guidance

Prefer writing pure helper functions as `constexpr` by default. If the body is valid, you get compile-time evaluation for free wherever constants are needed, and no overhead at runtime. Reserve `consteval` for functions that have *no* meaningful runtime use.
